{{Orphan|date=February 2018}}
'''Reed's rules''' are a set of guidelines developed by [[Joseph O. Reed]] in interpretation of [[Paediatrics|pediatric]] [[radiology]].<ref>Haller Jo, Slovis TL. Introduction to Radiology in Clinical Pediatrics. Year Book Medical Publishers, Inc. 1984.</ref>
==Reed's rules== Reed's rules are as follows: #''On every [[Chest radiograph|chest film]], read the abdominal portion as you would read an abdominal film. #''Knowledge of [[anatomy]] is the key to correct radiographic diagnosis. #''The [[airway]] should be visible on all normal chest films. #''A mass must be seen in two planes. #''An [[esophagram]] must be done on any child with unexplained [[respiratory disease]]. #''In unilateral hyperexpansion of the [[lung]]s, you must see how the air moves. Mediastinal position is critical to this determination. #''Always review all old films to assess new ones properly. Subtle findings can be missed easily when a single previous examination is reviewed. #''The abdominal examination should include a minimum of three views—supine, prone and erect. #''On every abdominal examination, evaluate the chest as if you were looking at a chest film. #''In obstruction of the [[Lumen (anatomy)|lumen]], there should be proximal [[distention]]. #''During [[intravenous urography]], keep taking films as long as you are getting needed information. #''Try to find the effects of the mass on adjacent organs on each abdominal film. Draw the mass, if necessary. #''After you have defined the mass, find the center of the [[lesion]]. Then consider all structures, gross and microscopic, near the center of the lesion as possible sources of the mass. Think skin to skin. #''The [[periosteum]] is not normally seen. #''When viewing an extremity, try to imagine the appearance of the patient. An excellent example is [[bowed legs]] or [[knock knees]].
